description: The ability to transfer the emotional bond from a person who has died onto their memory
name: Acceptance of Loss

description:
Distrusting yourself. Alientation is the inverse of paranoia, which involves distrusting someone or something outside of yourself.

Also called: Distrust
name: Alienation

description: The feeling admiration or astonishment (wonder) mixed with fear or respect, often inspired by something that seems powerful
name: Awe

description: The emotion associated with discovering that one's prediction was wrong.
name: Being Wrong

description: The experience of purging strong emotions. Clearing or purifying by getting rid of unhealthy tension.
name: Catharsis

description:
The feeling of being bewildered or unclear

Also called: Bewilderment, Perplexity
name: Confusion

description:
Feeling linked or bonded to others.

Also called: Community
name: Connection

description:
The feeling of being genuinely afraid of something and simultaneously bold enough to face it.

Also called: Bravery
name: Courage

description: When we feel we have some idea about an answer, but are unconfident about what that answer is. The active form of wonder. Where the first form of wonder is passive (essentially pausing in astonishment as a miracle washes over you), curiosity is active.
name: Curiosity

description:
Sense of detachment from what is happening

Also called: Resignation
name: Dissociation

description:
Anxiety or mental suffering that you have not chosen

Also called: Stress, Anxiety
name: Distress

description: Sharing a conflict faced by a character through the perspective of a character you already identify with
name: Double Identification

description: The feeling of understanding another person's actions. You may not condone the actions or identify with the person, but you accept that their actions weren't wrong
name: Empathy

description: The feeling of knowing and claiming your rights. You feel that you have the freedom and power to control what happens to you.
name: Empowerment

description: Stress that you have chosen
name: Eustress

description: Despair in the face of a meaningless universe.
name: Existential Nausea

description: An emotional response to the perceived resistance to the fulfillment of an individual's will or goal. Frustration is likely to increase when a will or goal is denied or blocked.
name: Frustration

description: Loving others for who they are, not for who we want them to be.
name: Generous Love

description: Satisfaction that a character you identify with gets what they want
name: Gratification

description: Recognizing, in a character's experience, a conflict that you have experienced
name: Identification

description: Absorbing or engrossing involvement in a story. You might feel as though you've been swallowed by the story.
name: Immersion

description: Affection, attraction, and emotional attachment
name: Love

description: Having thoughts unrelated to a specific task
name: Mind Wandering

description: A clear sense of what is right and what is wrong
name: Moral Omniscience

description:
The feeling that you are prepared to handle a variety of situations

Also called: Agility, Flexibility, Preparedness
name: Nimbleness

description: The belief the positive outcomes are more likely than negative ones
name: Optimism

description: A feeling of threat triggered by environmental irregularities
name: Paranoia

description: Realizing that there are things you could do to improve as a person
name: Ready to Grow

description: Learning something you have learned in the past and partially forgotten
name: Relearning

description: Feeling comfortable enough to experience emotions after feeling numb to emotions because of traumatic experiences
name: Released Emotion Brake

description: The easing of distress
name: Relief

description: Relief from the negative feelings you experience when you fail (self-loathing, self-hatred, rumination, etc.)
name: Resilience

description:
Resentful anger aroused by an act that you believe is immoral.

Also called: Outrage
name: Righteousness

description: Resentful anger aroused by an act that you believe is immoral and has been harmful to you
name: Righteousness + Identification

description: Accepting yourself without shame or disgust
name: Self-Acceptance

description: The belief that you are capable of accomplishing a specific goal
name: Self-Efficacy

description: Recognizing that you resemble a character being satirized in a story. Because you recognize that you are not perfect, you are able to laugh at yourself.
name: Self-Irony

description: Affection for your own nature, flaws and all.
name: Self-Love

description: Believing that you can rely on your own abilities to navigate the world
name: Self-Trust

description: A doubting or questioning state of mind
name: Skepticism

description: Spirits raised without intoxication
name: Sober Uplift

description: An elevated view (God's-Eye view) of a situation
name: Superiority

description: Being unsure how to evaluate something that is unfamiliar
name: Suspended Judgment

description: The state of imagining possibilities that do not exist
name: Thinking "What If?"

description: A feeling of being united in understanding with other people
name: Togetherness

description: a peaceful calm state, without worry
name: Tranquility

description: An uplifting emotional experience of discovery. As Fletcher puts it, wonder is “life through the eyes of a child" (16). It is like pausing in astonishment as a miracle washes over you (Fletcher 84).
name: Wonder
